<subSubSection pageNumber="627" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="627">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="627">Note:</emphasis>
Linnaeus explicitly cited as a synonym the validly published 
<taxonomicName authority="Huds. (1762) in Syst. Nat." authorityYear="1762" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Sphaerophoraceae" genus="Lichen" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Fungi" order="Lecanorales" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="globosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="627">Lichen globosus</emphasis>
Huds. (1762) in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="627">Syst. Nat.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ed. 12, but not in the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="627">Mantissa</emphasis>
account. This was overlooked by 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Jørgensen">Jorgensen</normalizedToken>
&amp; al. (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="627">Bot. J. Linn. Soc.</emphasis>
115: 318, 377, f. 36. 1994), who accepted 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Howe’s">Howe's</normalizedToken>
typification (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="627">
Bull. Torrey Bot. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Club’i">Club'i</normalizedToken>
</emphasis>
9: 201. 1912) using 1273.251 (LINN). However, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Linnaeus’">Linnaeus'</normalizedToken>
name must be homotypic with that of Hudson, which has been typified by Wedin (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="627">Pl. Syst. Evol.</emphasis>
187: 230-231. 1993).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
